answer: Well it is really on a case by case basis. In theory, SELECT's should *always* return a query object. Unless something is interfering... like if the query contains multiple sql statements, so we would need to see the actual query. As an aside, do not use # signs with isDefined. That function expects the *name* of a variable, ie a string. As I mentioned [in the comments](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/6379730/check-query-results-if-no-data-is-returned#comment7473686_6379730), using # signs means causes the variable to be evaluated, triggering the very error you are trying to prevent :)
